<subSubSection id="C3346522FFEBB074FF00FE9F1A28E5EB" pageId="1" pageNumber="317" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B9136A9FFEBB074FF00FE9F1D27E536" blockId="1.[151,1437,363,715]" pageId="1" pageNumber="317">
<emphasis id="B95AEABBFFEBB074FF00FE9F1863E6EF" bold="true" box="[151,266,363,390]" pageId="1" pageNumber="317">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. The genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C2E4D2AFFEBB074FE0CFE981BEFE6EF" authority="Park &amp; Kim" authorityName="Park &amp; Kim" authorityYear="2020" box="[411,646,364,390]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Halista" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95AEABBFFEBB074FE0CFE981884E6EF" box="[411,493,364,390]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="317">Halista</emphasis>
Park &amp; Kim
</taxonomicName>
is superficially similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C2E4D2AFFEBB074FC2EFE981DDBE6EF" authority="Walker, 1864" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1864" box="[953,1202,364,390]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Frisilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95AEABBFFEBB074FC2EFE981D64E6EF" box="[953,1037,364,390]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="317">Frisilia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFBF4B58FFEBB074FB80FE981DDBE6EF" author="Walker, F." box="[1047,1202,364,390]" pageId="1" pageNumber="317" refId="ref6073" refString="Walker, F. (1864) List of the specimens of Lepidopterous insects in the collection of the British museum. Part XXIX. Tineites. British Museum, London, 795 pp." type="book" year="1864">Walker, 1864</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, with atypical labial palpus. However, it is defined by the uniquely specialized 2 
<superScript id="7C5B9BE1FFEBB074FCA1FE7B1A2FE6F4" attach="left" box="[822,838,399,413]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="317">nd</superScript>
segment of the labial palpus which is shovel-shaped, broadened, concaved on inner surface, with a minute spine-like 3 
<superScript id="7C5B9BE1FFEBB074FCFEFE471A1EE6A8" attach="left" box="[873,887,435,449]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="317">rd</superScript>
segment, whereas in the latter, it is long, strongly angled, covered with rough scales in male. The other diagnostic morphological characters differentiating the new genus from all other genera of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2E4D2AFFEBB074FE63FE081BF3E57F" authorityName="Le Marchand" authorityYear="1947" box="[500,666,508,534]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Lecithoceridae</taxonomicName>
are the following: the front leg with long hair-like scales above; the hindwing venation with very unusual M 
<subScript id="17AA34ECFFEBB074FDCDFDC61B0BE529" attach="left" box="[602,610,562,576]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="317">2</subScript>
extending from near base of R-vein to termen; the male genitalia lacking caudal process in juxta; the abdomen with a long hair-pencil arising from segment V.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9136A9FFEBB074FF50FD9C1A28E5EB" blockId="1.[151,1437,363,715]" box="[199,833,616,643]" pageId="1" pageNumber="317">
The new genus belongs to the subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="4C2E4D2AFFEBB074FD04FD9C1A54E5EB" authorityName="Le Marchand" authorityYear="1947" box="[659,829,616,642]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Lecithocerinae">Lecithocerinae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3346522FFEBB074FF50FD781BA1E5A3" pageId="1" pageNumber="317" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B9136A9FFEBB074FF50FD781BA1E5A3" blockId="1.[151,1437,363,715]" pageId="1" pageNumber="317">
<emphasis id="B95AEABBFFEBB074FF50FD781821E5CF" bold="true" box="[199,328,652,678]" pageId="1" pageNumber="317">Etymology</emphasis>
. The generic name is derived from the Greek, 
<emphasis id="B95AEABBFFEBB074FCF5FD781AE7E5CF" box="[866,910,652,678]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="317">hali</emphasis>
(= sea) with a Greek superlative ending - 
<emphasis id="B95AEABBFFEBB074FAFAFD791CFCE5CF" box="[1389,1429,653,678]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="317">ista</emphasis>
, referring to the 
<typeStatus id="5495880BFFEBB074FED1FD45181FE5A2" box="[326,374,689,715]" pageId="1" pageNumber="317">type</typeStatus>
locality on the Pacific Ocean.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
